primary_outcome.description:
The Berlin Definition of Acute Respiratory Distress Syndrome:
Timing: Within 1 week of a known clinical insult or new or worsening respiratory symptoms;
Chest imaging: Bilateral opacities-not fully explained by effusions, lobar/lung collapse, or nodules;
Origin of edema: Respiratory failure not fully explained by cardiac failure or fluid overload. Need objective assessment (eg, echocardiography) to exclude hydrostatic edema if no risk factor present;
Oxygenation:
Mild 200 mm Hg <PaO2/FIO2≤ 300 mm Hg with PEEP or CPAP ≥5 cm H2O; Moderate 100 mm Hg <PaO2/FIO2≤ 200 mm Hg with PEEP ≥5 cm H2O Severe PaO2/FIO2≤ 100 mm Hg with PEEP ≥5 cm H2O

criteria.textblock:
        Inclusion Criteria:

          -  Selective operation;

          -  Cardiac surgery with cardiopulmonary bypass;

          -  Adult patients over 18 years old;

          -  Signed informed consent

        Exclusion Criteria:

          -  emergency surgery;

          -  previous cardiac surgery;

          -  previous liver cirrhosis;

          -  preoperative pulmonary function problems: pulmonary insufficiency such as hypoxemia,
             pulmonary inflammation, respiratory failure, etc.;

          -  preoperative ventilator or extracorporeal membrane oxygenation support;

          -  preoperative pulmonary function problems;

          -  ARDS occurred during the operation;

          -  death occurred during the operation;

          -  extracorporeal membrane oxygenation support was needed after the operation or CPB was
             performed again within 3 days.
